  <media:group>
   <media:title>Going Reactive With Spring WebFlux, Kotlin Coroutines, and RSocket</media:title>
   <media:content url="https://www.youtube.com/v/FcwR34DFqIc?version=3" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="640" height="390"/>
   <media:thumbnail url="https://i3.ytimg.com/vi/FcwR34DFqIc/hqdefault.jpg" width="480" height="360"/>
   <media:description>Spring 5 introduced two major new features, native support of the reactive programming paradigm and the possibility to use Kotlin. There are lots of useful Kotlin extensions in Spring and the new reactive stack looks really appealing for building microservices.

In this session, Oleh Dokuka and Anton Arhipov will cover the process of building a chat application with Spring, Kotlin, and RSocket. They will start with a standard Spring Boot application implemented with Spring MVC. During the session, they will migrate the application to Spring WebFlux with Kotlin coroutines, add non-blocking database access, and add RSocket for streaming the events from the backend to the UI to make the application fully reactive.

Speakers:

Oleh Dokuka @olehdokuka

Oleh is a Software Engineer who has experience with reactive technology both as a user and a developer. Java Champion. Co-author of the book "Hands‑On Reactive Programming in Spring 5". Works on RSocket and improves Project Reactor.

Host:
Anton Arhipov @antonarhipov

Anton is a Developer Advocate in the Kotlin team at JetBrains. His professional interests include programming languages and developer tooling. Java Champion since 2014. Anton is also a co-organizer of DevClub.eu, a local developer community in Tallinn, Estonia.</media:description>
